Let \mathcal {F} be a fibred category with base \mathcal {C}, and consider a diagram of morphisms in \mathcal {C}
       S  \xleftarrow { \alpha }       S'  \overset { \beta _1 }{ \underset { \beta _2 }{ \leftleftarrows }}        S''     
such that \alpha \beta _1= \alpha \beta _2;
this diagram is said to be \mathcal {F}-exact if, for every pair ( \xi , \eta ) of elements of \mathcal {F}_S, the diagram of sets

450Equationfga3.i-a.1-definition-1.3-equationfga3.i-a.1-definition-1.3-equation.xml+fga3.i-a.1-definition-1.3          \operatorname {Hom} ( \xi , \eta )  \xrightarrow { \alpha ^*}          \operatorname {Hom} ( \alpha ^*( \xi ), \alpha ^*( \eta ))  \overset { \beta _1^* }{ \underset { \beta _2^* }{ \rightrightarrows }}           \operatorname {Hom} ( \gamma ^*( \xi ), \gamma ^*( \eta ))       \tag{+}       

(where \gamma = \alpha \beta _1= \alpha \beta _2) is exact.

For the functor F to be pro-representable, it is necessary and sufficient that it satisfy the two following conditions: TO-DO: the following list should be i, ii
F commutes with finite products;
for every algebra A \in \mathcal {C} and every homomorphism A \to A' in \mathcal {C} such that the diagram A \to A' \rightrightarrows A' \otimes _A A' is exact (cf. FGA 3.I, §A, Definition 1.2), the diagram F(A) \to F(A') \rightrightarrows F(A' \otimes _A A') is also exact.
Furthermore, it suffices to verify condition (ii) in the case where A is local, and when, further, we are in one of the two following cases: TO-DO: the following list should be a, b
A is a free module over A;
the quotient module A'/A is an A-module of length 1.
